03729nmm a2200481Ia 9780791481738DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780791481738  a(DE-B1597)684067  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB3317b.F92 2006 7aPHI0230002bisacsh04a1091 aFroese, Katrin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNietzsche, Heidegger, and Daoist Thought :bCrossing Paths In-Between /cKatrin Froese. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (266 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Chinese Philosophy and Culture00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tWays of Being, Ways of Thinking -- tFinite Wanderers -- tThe Importance of Nothing -- tHierarchy and Equality -- tWoman's Eclipse -- tBeing(s) in Between -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, Katrin Froese juxtaposes the Daoist texts of Laozi and Zhuangzi with the thought of Nietzsche and Heidegger to argue that there is a need for rethinking the idea of a cosmological whole. By moving away from the quest for certainty, Froese suggests a way of philosophizing that does not seek to capture the whole, but rather becomes a means of affirming a connection to it, one that celebrates difference rather than eradicating it.Human beings have a vague awareness of the infinite, but they are nevertheless finite beings. Froese maintains that rather than bemoaning the murkiness of knowledge, the thinkers considered here celebrate the creativity and tendency to wander through that space of not knowing, or "in-between-ness." However, for Neitzsche and the early Heidegger, this in-between-ness can often produce a sense of meaninglessness that sends individuals on a frenetic quest to mark out space that is uniquely their own. Laozi and Zhuangzi, on the other hand, paint a portrait of the self that provides openings for others rather than deliberately forging an identity that it can claim as its own. In this way, human beings can become joyful wanderers that revel in the movements of the Dao and are comfortable with their own finitude. Froese also suggests that Nietzsche and Heidegger are philosophers at a crossroads, for they both exemplify the modern emphasis on self-creation and at the same time share the Daoist insight into the perils of excessive egoism that can lead to misguided attempts to master the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aTaoism. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Taoist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791481738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791481738/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles